flowRoot.flowPara: NETs at a very large scale raise concerns of hubris, that we may have undue confidence in our ability to control global biogeochemical cycles. Comparing NETs deployment levels in scenarios to the global carbon budget, CO₂ drawdowns equivalent to the entire natural lank sink have been proposed (i.e. all CO₂ sequestration on Earth that is currently performed by plants). This implies an enormous scope for adverse and unintended side-effects.

NETs dis-incentivise near-term mitigation. The severity of this mitigation obstruction can be observed in comparable scenarios for meeting 2⁰C, where one scenario constrains carbon capture (CCS) technologies. Mitigation occurs faster and deeper in the absence of CCS, reaching a gap of 9.1 GtCO₂ by 2030 - equivalent to the total annual emissions of China.

Scaling up NETs faces great social and technical challenges. As of 2018, three major BECCS demonstration plants exist. Yet a typical 2°C scenario requires the planning, funding, construction and operation of more than 50,000 plants already by 2040, and an additional 100,000 by 2050. From an ethical perspective it is significant that the collateral in this bet, future generations, have no say in the terms of the gamble.
